# PWAFire Style Guide

## Code Formatting

### Indentation
- Use 2 spaces for indentation (no tabs)
- Consistent across TypeScript, JavaScript, JSON, and Markdown files

### Line Length
- Soft limit: 100 characters
- Hard limit: 120 characters
- Break long lines at logical points

### Semicolons
- Always use semicolons
- No ASI (Automatic Semicolon Insertion) reliance

### Quotes
- Use double quotes for strings: `"hello"`
- Use backticks for template literals: `` `Hello ${name}` ``
- Consistent across all files

### Trailing Commas
- Use trailing commas in multi-line objects/arrays
- Example:
  ```typescript
  const config = {
    prop1: value1,
    prop2: value2,  // trailing comma
  };
  ```

## TypeScript Style

### Type Annotations
- Explicit types for function parameters
- Return type inference where obvious
- Example:
  ```typescript
  export const apiName = async (config: ConfigType): Promise<ResponseType> => {
    // implementation
  };
  ```

### Interface vs Type
- Use `type` for simple types and unions
- Use `interface` for object shapes that may be extended
- Keep type definitions close to usage

### Async/Await
- Prefer async/await over promises
- Always handle errors internally
- Example:
  ```typescript
  export const apiName = async (params: Type) => {
    try {
      const result = await someOperation();
      return { ok: true, message: "Success", data: result };
    } catch (error) {
      return {
        ok: false,
        message: error instanceof Error ? error.message : "Failed"
      };
    }
  };
  ```

### Null vs Undefined
- Use `null` for intentional absence
- Let TypeScript infer `undefined` for uninitialized
- Avoid mixing both in same context

## Function Style

### Arrow Functions
- Use arrow functions for consistency
- Example:
  ```typescript
  export const functionName = async (params: Type) => {
    // implementation
  };
  ```

### Function Length
- Keep functions short and focused (under 30 lines)
- Extract complex logic into helper functions
- One responsibility per function

### Parameters
- Maximum 3 parameters
- Use object parameter for more than 3
- Example:
  ```typescript
  // Good
  export const apiName = async (config: { prop1: string; prop2: number }) => {};

  // Avoid
  export const apiName = async (prop1: string, prop2: number, prop3: boolean, prop4: string) => {};
  ```

## Naming Style

### Variables
- camelCase: `const userName = "John"`
- Descriptive names: `getUserData()` not `get()`
- Boolean prefix: `isValid`, `hasPermission`, `canEdit`

### Constants
- SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE for true constants
- Example: `const MAX_RETRY_ATTEMPTS = 3`
- Use uppercase sparingly - only for values that never change

### Functions
- Verb-noun pattern: `copyText()`, `webShare()`, `accessFonts()`
- Action-oriented: what it does, not what it is
- Consistent prefixes:
  - `get` - retrieve data
  - `set` - store data
  - `is`/`has`/`can` - boolean checks
  - `handle` - event handlers

### Types/Interfaces
- PascalCase: `ResponseType`, `ConfigOptions`
- Descriptive suffixes: `UserConfig`, `ApiResponse`, `ErrorMessage`

## File Structure

### Exports
- Named exports preferred over default exports
- Export at declaration:
  ```typescript
  export const apiName = async () => {};
  ```
- Group related exports in index files

### Imports
- Order: external, internal, relative
- Group by type:
  ```typescript
  // External dependencies
  import { something } from "external-package";

  // Internal modules
  import { helper } from "./utils";
  import { type } from "./types";

  // Relative imports
  import { config } from "../config";
  ```

### Module Organization
- One primary export per file
- Helper functions in same file if small
- Extract to separate file if reusable

## Error Handling Style

### Never Throw
- All errors handled internally
- Return `{ ok: false, message }` format
- Example:
  ```typescript
  export const apiName = async (params: Type) => {
    try {
      const result = await operation();
      return { ok: true, message: "Success", data: result };
    } catch (error) {
      return {
        ok: false,
        message: error instanceof Error ? error.message : "Operation failed"
      };
    }
  };
  ```

### Error Messages
- User-friendly, actionable messages
- No technical jargon in user-facing errors
- Consistent format: `"Failed to {action}: {reason}"`

## Comments Style

### Code Comments
- **DO NOT USE CODE COMMENTS**
- Write self-documenting code instead
- Use clear variable and function names
- Extract complex logic into named functions

### Documentation Comments
- JSDoc only for public API functions
- Keep brief - focus on usage, not implementation
- Example:
  ```typescript
  /**
   * Copy text to clipboard
   * @returns {Promise<{ok: boolean, message: string}>}
   */
  export const copyText = async (text: string) => {};
  ```

### TODO Comments
- Avoid TODOs - create issues instead
- If necessary, include issue number:
  ```typescript
  // TODO(#123): Implement retry logic
  ```

## Testing Style

### Dynamic Generation
- Generate tests from exports, don't hardcode
- Example:
  ```javascript
  Object.keys(pwafire).forEach(apiName => {
    if (typeof pwafire[apiName] === 'function') {
      // Generate test
    }
  });
  ```

### Test Configuration
- Store test configs in objects
- Make tests data-driven
- Example:
  ```javascript
  const apiConfigs = {
    webShare: {
      title: 'Web Share',
      params: () => [{ title: 'Test', url: location.href }]
    }
  };
  ```

## Git Style

### Commit Messages
- Format: `type(scope): brief description`
- Types: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`
- Keep first line under 72 characters
- Body: explain why, not what
- Example:
  ```
  feat(clipboard): add copyText API

  Provides simple interface for clipboard operations with built-in
  error handling and consistent response format.

  Co-Authored-By: Claude Sonnet 4.5 <noreply@anthropic.com>
  ```

### Branch Names
- Format: `type/brief-description`
- Use hyphens, not underscores
- Keep short but descriptive
- Examples:
  - `feat/add-clipboard-api`
  - `fix/screen-share-naming`
  - `chore/update-docs`

## HTML/CSS Style (Test Console)

### HTML
- Semantic HTML5 elements
- Minimal structure, maximum JS
- No inline styles
- Example:
  ```html
  <div class="test-grid" id="test-grid">
    <!-- Populated by JS -->
  </div>
  ```

### CSS
- No box-shadow (user preference)
- Monochrome palette: black (#000), grays (#111-#888), white (#fff)
- BEM-like naming: `.test-card`, `.feature-item`
- Mobile-first responsive design

### JavaScript (Browser)
- ES6+ features
- Module pattern
- Dynamic DOM generation
- No jQuery or heavy frameworks

## Documentation Style

### README
- Clear, concise examples
- Highlight key features first
- Emphasize built-in error handling
- Show both root and scoped imports
- No try/catch in examples (error handling is built-in)

### Code Examples
- Realistic use cases
- Complete, runnable code
- Show response format
- Example:
  ```typescript
  import { copyText } from "pwafire/clipboard";

  const { ok, message } = await copyText("Hello World");

  if (ok) {
    console.log("Success:", message);
  } else {
    console.log("Failed:", message);
  }
  ```

## Performance Considerations

### Bundle Size
- Tree-shakeable exports
- Scoped imports for single features
- No barrel export overhead

### Runtime
- Minimal abstractions
- Direct API calls
- No unnecessary async operations

### Memory
- Clean up event listeners
- No memory leaks in callbacks
- Proper async cleanup

## Accessibility

### Test Console
- Keyboard navigation support
- Clear focus indicators
- Semantic HTML structure
- High contrast (monochrome design)

### Error Messages
- Screen reader friendly
- Clear, descriptive text
- No jargon or technical codes
